<font color="#FF0000">WHEN GOD DECLARES WAR</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec 10 18:53:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Class Lass <br><br>
I have purposely delayed responding because I wanted to hear my brothers speak. They sound very much like the Marines of 1st platoon when we gathered for our first reunion after 30 year, last February. <br><br>
We shared the same thoughts concerns, and believe I have read about here. What was unique however was that all of us had individually encountered a divine presence in Vietnam and we found it once again present at our reunion. The awesome presence of the power of love, grace, honor, peace, joy, laughter and trust that we all once knew in the jungles of Vietnam was found present again in our midst. <br><br>
I did not preach, but listened and in the end it was our lieutenant, Lt. Larry Wilson our platoon commander who commended that the divine presence who had preserved us in battle was once again felt at our reunion. He questioned if we were for some unique reason spared greater harm because of God’s intervention in our behalf in Vietnam. <br><br>
Jerry Lucero had mentioned that he felt God’s presence with him while he lay playing dead at the foot of the enemy’s trench line. Others of hearing audible warnings and a sense of danger and divine protection in the midst of chaos in battle. I recounted how on at least nine occasions I should have been killed and there was no sound reason why I shouldn’t been. <br><br>
I want to thank you Class Lass for this thread. I will share my thoughts here without reservation and perhaps if permitted even in a pastoral voice because that is what I am and who I am today (what have you done since the war is a question often asked here). I received my Masters degree a couple of years ago in Christian Leadership from Fuller Theological Seminary in Pasadena, California. I have preached on radio, on Television and many times before a crowd of thousands. Much of what I share here is what I believe and since you asked for my response I will share it with you here. <br><br>
Some time ago I read an article written by a couple of Christian leaders in CHRISTIANITY TODAY, October 28, 1996, Vol 40, No 12, page 14. <br>
“What happens when God Declares War,” is the title of that article. It was the first time I had read anyone who would write about God as I see him, as a Divine Warrior. I share some of those thoughts here and if anyone would like a copy of that message I will gladly e-mail them a complete copy. <br><br>
In the introduction of that article they wrote:<br>
 <br>
“The violence of God can only be understood in the shadow of the Cross.” <br><br>
I was not religious in Vietnam except to pray as any other one of us would under the circumstances we found ourselves in. The only prayer I knew then was the Lord’s prayer, yet there is no doubt now, thirty years later as I look back, as I reflect upon what occurred then and there, that I experienced several incidents of powerful protection as well as divine intervention which could not be accounted for by any other means. <br><br>
But even then those divine encounters did not change me. I just remembered them as strange phenomena, which I could not understand and forgot about them after my return. Ten years would pass before I like MTF would find who Jesus was. Before I would remember the warrior God I had at my side in Vietnam.<br><br>
I met God or rather He met me when I thought I had no need for him. After all what need does a young handsome, Los Angeles Police officer have when he posses authority and good charms? Still there was emptiness within me that I could not satisfy with the company of women, booze or authority. <br><br>
Since then, I have all too well realized how His protective arms had been upon me in Vietnam in the midst of many of those battles. <br><br>
I now truly believe that God is a Divine Warrior and that He protects and honors those who he selects for certain tasks. <br><br>
Tom’s comment about CHAPLAIN PHILLIP NICHOLS death along with several others, by a land mine. Is followed by his comment that the Chaplain gave his life in service to his fellow man. That reminds me of what the Lord said to his disciples shortly before he gave his life for us. <br><br>
&quot;Greater love has no one than this, that one lay down his life for his friends.” Chaplain Nichols did that in his service by being there among the warriors in battle (John 15:13, NAS).<br><br>

